    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Neither needed — author's prior paragraph already explains it",
    "content": "**Neither the inline nor the TN is needed. The author's own text does the work.**\n\nIf the reader has already encountered a full paragraph explaining that 形而上 means \"meta-physics,\" that 上 means \"built upon phenomena\" (not \"generating from above\"), and that 形 = phenomena — then by the time they reach the 道德仁义礼 sentence, the conceptual apparatus is already in place. Adding a parenthetical or TN at that point would be *repeating what the author already said*. That is patronizing — and worse, it undermines the author's own expository skill by implying the reader needs the translator to re-explain what the author just explained.\n\n**The only thing needed:** Make sure the earlier explanatory paragraph is translated clearly and completely, preserving the 形/形而上/上 structure. If that paragraph lands well, the later sentence takes care of itself.\n\nI retract both my TN and inline suggestions. Trust the author's text."
  }
}
